author: TEDx Talks
description:
Kanning's talk aims to challenge how we view and approach emergency room overuse, particularly in pediatric care. Through her research and experience as a pre-med student deeply involved in public health policy and emergency medicine, she has seen firsthand how non-emergent visits to the ER create an overwhelming burden on healthcare systems. Families often rush to the ER for issues like mild fevers, colds, or minor injuries—cases that could be handled by primary care or at home with the right knowledge.

But what if we inverted the way we think about these visits? Instead of seeing them as a drain on resources, we can view them as missed educational opportunities. The concept of inversion is all about flipping perspectives, and her vision is to show how shifting our approach from reactive to proactive healthcare can transform how patients and families engage with medical systems. Imagine if families had the tools and education to understand when to seek emergency care and when altern
title: Does your child need the ER or urgent care? | Destiny Kanning | TEDxMSU

description: Dr. Renée St. Jacques reveals the psychological foundations that make teams truly excel. Drawing on her experience as a licensed psychologist, researcher, executive coach, and former Microsoft leader, she shows how emotional intelligence and human-centered leadership can transform performance and culture. Her talk offers practical, science-based insights for building teams that are not only effective, but deeply human. Dr. Renee St Jacques blends human behavior expertise as a licensed psychologist, researcher, and certified executive coach with over 20 years in Corporate America, including a notable tenure at Microsoft. Focused on maximizing team and leadership impact, she delivers expert solutions that enhance emotional intelligence, leadership acumen, and organizational culture, fostering greater humanity and impact to transform leadership for a new generation. description: Fabio Pressi, CEO of A2A E-Mobility and President of Motus-E, argues that mobility is no longer just about movement, it’s about data, power, and the future of cities. With over 20 years in smart mobility and leadership roles across Infoblu, Telepass, and Atlantia, Fabio reveals how digital intelligence is reshaping transportation, infrastructure, and the way we live. Drawing on insights from his 2025 book Digital Mobility, he shows why data will drive the next great mobility revolution. Fabio Pressi, born in 1966, is CEO and President of A2A E-Mobility since 2021 and President of Motus-E since 2024. He teaches at LUISS Business School and published Digital Mobility in 2025. With 20+ years in smart mobility, he was CEO of Infoblu, CDO at Telepass, and spent 10+ years at Atlantia, leading digital product and big data projects. He holds a degree in Electronic Engineering from the Polytechnic University of Turin. This talk was given at a TEDx event using the TED conference format but inde

Rather than being defined by one place or moment, they learned that every new environment added something valuable to who they are today. give me another title A passionate traveler with a creative spirit, she thrives on exploring new places, ideas, and perspectives. author: TEDx Talks
description: The talk explores how the fear of missing out shapes our decisions, especially as teenagers constantly torn between choices. Through personal stories and reflections, this talk shows how shifting our mindset from what we might miss to what we truly value can turn uncertainty into clarity — helping us embrace our unique paths without regret. Pranusha is a passionate learner with diverse interests in books, music, movies, and science, thriving on creativity and curiosity. With strong skills in creative design, critical thinking, and problem-solving, she brings fresh perspectives to every challenge. Enthusiastic and open-minded, she enjoys venturing into new horizons and embracing growth. Driven by a strong desire to succeed, she aims to make a meaningful and lasting impact through her ideas. author: TEDx Talks
description:
Most people see clutter as a chore, but what if it actually holds opportunity and possibility? In this talk, Deirdre Greaney explores why releasing things can feel so difficult and why doing it can bring relief, growth, and healing. Through personal stories, cultural traditions, insights from neuroscience, and her Three Doors of Letting Go method, she shows how clearing space around us can create space within us. Deirdre Greaney is a holistic coach and wellness practitioner whose work brings together energy healing, coaching, essential oils and natural living to support emotional balance and everyday wellbeing. After beginning her career in law and insurance, she transitioned into the wellness field, earning qualifications in bio-energy therapy, reflexology and aromatherapy, as well as life and business coaching with neuroscience. She now helps people reconnect with themselves on energetic, emotional and practical levels.

Deirdre leads group and individual sessions that combine oils,
title: Why is it so hard to let go of clutter? | Deirdre Greaney | TEDxTraleeWomen

author: TEDx Talks
description:
As the digital revolution reshapes every industry, healthcare stands at a pivotal crossroads. This talk explores how the convergence of artificial intelligence, machine learning, and predictive analytics is transforming not only how we diagnose and treat illness, but how we design the very systems and spaces in which healthcare delivery takes place.

From algorithm-driven patient triage to smart hospital infrastructures that adapt in real time, the future of healthcare lies in our ability to harmonize human expertise with intelligent technologies. But this transformation is about more than machines—it’s about trust, ethics, equity, and access. How do we build digital tools that enhance, rather than replace, human compassion? How can we ensure these systems serve all populations fairly, not just the digitally privileged? And what role must clinicians, designers, and technologists play together in shaping this evolution?

This talk offers a visionary yet grounded look at the future-read
title: Do algorithms design future ready medical systems? | Zisis Kozlakidis | TEDxMedUniGraz

description: When we were unborn children, we exchanged cells with our mums. Hear the incredible story of these cells and what it might mean for you… Thomas studied Technical Chemistry at TU Graz and received his doctorate in Medical Sciences from Med Uni Graz (PhD equivalent, with distinction) in 2009. During his thesis, he worked on rare cell analysis in the context of non-invasive prenatal diagnostics, focusing on fetal cells circulating in the peripheral blood of pregnant women. In 2014, he was awarded a three-year Marie Curie Fellowship, allowing him to join the lab of Prof. Stahlberg in Gothenburg, Sweden, where he expanded his knowledge of single-cell RNA analyses. Back in Austria, he habilitated in Cell Biology, Histology, and Embryology (venia docendi) in 2018 and was appointed 2nd Deputy Chair of the Division of Cell Biology, Histology, and Embryology. In 2021, he started a research group and became the leading principal investigator of an international consortium running a 5.3 million U
title: Microchimerism - not all human cells in your body come from you | Thomas Kroneis | TEDxMedUniGraz

author: TEDx Talks
description:
In a world engineered by curated feeds, invisible algorithms, and conversations filtered through screens, how do we stay true to who we really are?
Adole-Sense explores what happens when an entire generation grows up online - where every like, comment, and feed doesn’t just observe us… it quietly shapes us.
As a 15-year-old global student growing up inside the digital ecosystem, I’ve seen how platforms don’t simply connect young people. They profile us, predict us, and emotionally engineer us. The internet was built for discovery and 'good', but teens like us are growing up inside systems designed for manipulation.
The future is being coded right now, and it’s time we keep our voices real, human, and our own! Tamas is a 15-year-old international student based in France, originally from Hungary, with Russian and Central Asian roots, and was born in Georgia. Growing up in a diplomatic family—with a father working for the United Nations and a mother involved in journalism—he has lived on
title: adole-sense | Tamas Landesz | TEDxMedUniGraz

author: TEDx Talks
description:
What comes to mind when you hear the word “scientist”? For many, it’s an image of someone distant, elite—even arrogant.
 
In this talk, I challenge that stereotype by sharing my personal journey into science, one that didn’t follow the traditional path. I show how science is not a closed-off world for a chosen few, but a way of thinking that belongs to all of us.
 
Through honest storytelling and reflection, I break down the myth of the “untouchable, unreachable scientist” and make the case for a more human, inclusive approach, where curiosity, humility, and collaboration matter more than credentials or ego.
 
My goal is to empower the audience to see science differently: not as a cold, exclusive system, but as a creative and collective effort we can all be part of.
 
The future starts today—let’s transform the scientific landscape into a space where people are welcomed in and have the opportunity to explore, contribute, and lead. Sahra is a molecular biologist with a background in ca
title: Who is a Scientist? Shaping Innovation from the Heart  | Sahra Tasdelen | TEDxMedUniGraz

author: TEDx Talks
description:
It took doctors a decade to find his diagnosis. It took AI ten seconds. This talk reveals how technology—which can feel cold and detached—is actually the key to reclaiming humanity in healthcare. We can use algorithms to dismantle bias and burnout, empowering patients and freeing doctors to truly see and heal. 

Key Takeaway:
Your health, your data, your future. Roi's background is a patchwork of patient advocacy, tech innovation, and hard-won personal experience. He has lived the challenges of navigating chronic illness, often finding himself forced to become his own advocate. This experience led him to create patient-led communities, as he understands the power of shared experience and collective voice. On the tech side, he dove headfirst into the world of medical device startups and developed the Help+ app, driven by a desire to use technology to bridge gaps in healthcare. He is not a traditional “expert”; he is a patient who has become a problem-solver, a disruptor, and a relentle
title: The Algorithm Will See You Now | Roi Shternin | TEDxMedUniGraz

author: TEDx Talks
description:
Not every innovation begins with billion-dollar ideas in high-tech labs. Sometimes it starts with something as ordinary as a roll of tape - or as profound as a moment in the ICU.

In this talk, medical students from Graz share two stories - one simple, one tragic- to show that innovation isn’t about the size of a problem, but the courage to act on it. That spirit led them to found MIOSIS, a space where students turn ideas into solutions that matter.

Because real innovation begins the moment someone decides, this can’t stay the way it is. MIOSIS (Medical Innovations of Students in Styria) is where bold ideas to shape the future of healthcare emerge - not from textbooks, but from collaboration, curiosity and courage.
Founded at the Medical University of Graz, MIOSIS connects students from diverse fields to share knowledge, exchange perspectives and co-create solutions that address pressing issues in medicine and care.In open, supportive environments, members are encouraged to grow, cha
title: How small ideas change everything | MIOSIS Medical Innovation of Students in Styria | TEDxMedUniGraz

author: TEDx Talks
description:
What happens to your brain when you consume the news - and why does it sometimes leave you feeling anxious, overwhelmed or powerless?
 
BBC journalist, presenter, and podcast host Hannah Gelbart explores the neuroscience of news consumption. She explains how scientists have discovered that distressing headlines and graphic images trigger our brain’s fight-or-flight response, with events happening thousands of kilometres away sparking real fear in our minds and bodies.
  
But research shows our brains are also drawn to bad news. We’re wired to seek out danger, novelty and answers. That’s why doomscrolling feels so addictive. Studies show we notice, remember and respond more strongly to negative news than to positive. It’s a survival mechanism with unintended consequences in the digital age.
 
And what can journalists learn from this?
 
Hannah talks about her experience of developing a new format for young people who may avoid traditional news but still want to be informed. ‘What in the
title: Addicted or Overwhelmed? Your brain on the news | Hannah Gelbart | TEDxMedUniGraz

author: TEDx Talks
description:
The talk discusses why our minds often misread tomorrow. We tend to imagine a single “future” and forget that there are many possible futures. We misunderstand probabilities, mistake randomness for patterns, and fall victim to false certainty or needless panic. In moments of crisis, our coping mechanisms make us postpone critical decisions that determine our future. Hype can blind us to the difference between true hope and wishful thinking.
Drawing on insights from critical futurism, behavioral economics, statistics, psychology, and cognitive sciences, this talk exposes how biases obscure our vision of what may lie ahead. It offers practical strategies to spot mental traps, expand our thinking, and approach the future with clearer vision, greater confidence, and a sense of agency.

Key takeaway:
We can’t predict the future—but by spotting mental traps, we can think and ACT about it more wisely, creatively, and courageously. Lukasz is a researcher in foresight and interdisciplinary stu
title: 10 Pitfalls in Future Thinking - and How to Avoid Them | Lukasz Nazarko | TEDxMedUniGraz

author: TEDx Talks
description:
What if we treated sexual education not as a topic of controversy, but as a powerful tool for prevention and safety?

This talk explores how comprehensive sexual education is one of the most effective strategies we have to reduce violence, support sexual health, and foster equality.

Drawing on recent international research and global standards, it unpacks how age-appropriate, rights-based education can shape the future - for example, by teaching consent, addressing harmful gender norms, and empowering young people to understand and protect themselves and others.

Sexual education is not just about information; it’s about prevention, boundaries, and safety. It equips individuals to navigate relationships with respect, awareness, and kindness.

The future is now, and it’s informed, inclusive, and safer for all.    Gudrun is a teacher, sexual educator, medical student, and PhD candidate at the University of Graz, researching sexual education in Austria and the German-speaking region. Ov
title: Let's have that talk: Rethinking sexual education | Gudrun Kern | TEDxMedUniGraz

author: TEDx Talks
description: Oggi la stampa e i giornalisti sono minacciati e la libertà di opinione è sotto attacco in molte regioni del mondo. Nel suo appassionato talk Désirée Klain racconta quanto sia importante sostenere reporter e fotografi, se vogliamo difendere il loro operato contro la corruzione, la criminalità, le derive autoritarie. Solo una stampa libera offre un argine contro le distorsioni della verità e della democrazia.  Today, press and journalists are under threat, as well as freedom of expression, in many areas of the world. In her passionate talk, Désirée Klain underscores the urgent need to support reporters and photojournalists in defending their work against corruption, crime, and authoritarianism. A free press remains one of the strongest safeguards against the distortion of truth and the erosion of democracy. Desiree Klain: giornalista, regista e direttrice artistica vanta oltre 30 anni di esperienza in ambito culturale e sociale. Collabora con il Corriere del Mezzogiorno e dirige festiv
title: Proteggiamo insieme la libertà di informazione | Désirée Klain | TEDxMantova

author: TEDx Talks
description:
The talk celebrates generations of Irish women who challenged patriarchy, survived violence, and pushed for social change—from early 20th-century rebels to modern feminist voices. Through stories of forgotten heroines and personal ancestry, it reveals how progress has always faced resistance. It calls for renewed revolutionary spirit to protect today’s freedoms. Dr. Mary McAuliffe is a historian, lecturer, and Director of Gender Studies at UCD. She specialises in Irish women's / gender history, traumas histories of gendered and sexual violence of Ireland's revolutionary period and histories of sexualities. She completed her BA (Hons), MA, and PhD at the School of History and Humanities, Trinity College, Dublin (TCD)

She is on the advisory committee on the representation of women's stories in the National Cultural Institutions. She is also on the advisory board of the Irish Association of Professional Historians (www.iaph.ie) and is a past President of the Women's History Association
title: Revolutionary Women | Mary McAuliffe | TEDxTraleeWomen

title: From Bathrooms to Board Rooms | Karen Ronan | TEDxTraleeWomen

description: What if everything you need, work, school, coffee, groceries, was just a short walk or bike ride away? Jayanna explores the concept of the 15-minute city, a bold vision for urban planning that prioritises people over traffic. From reducing emissions and improving health to strengthening communities and local economies, this talk reveals how rethinking city design can transform daily life. It’s not about taking away choices, it’s about creating better ones. With a creative spirit and a passion for family, Jayanna brings to the stage a fresh vision for urban life. Her talk investigates the idea of the “15-minute city”—a place where everything you need, from school to shops to green space, is within a short walk or bike ride. Jayanna explains how this model is already transforming cities like Paris and Melbourne, creating healthier, more connected communities. Her purpose is to inspire a future where cities are built around people—not just cars. This talk was given at a TEDx event using

How do you find inspiration? Children dress up as the characters they love to have fun, but as adults we lose that motivation. What if the people we admire can teach us something about ourselves? description:
This talk takes you on a journey from the womb to old age, revealing how rhythms and sound shape our brains, bodies and relationships at every stage of life. prepare to rethink what music truly does for us! Music is the driving force in Louise Kelly’s life. A Consultant Music Therapist and co-founder of Resilient Rhythms, Louise has spent over 25 years harnessing music’s transformative power to connect, regulate, and heal across all ages and settings.
Alongside her clinical practice, she lectures at university level on therapeutic music-making in education, equipping future teachers with creative, evidence-based tools for the classroom. A qualified ADHD and autism diagnostician, Louise also delivers neurodiversity training to businesses, schools, and organisations, helping them build inclusive cultures that celebrate difference.

Kathy Is the Run Your Life Coach. Her motto: Don't Let Life Run You.  She identifies as Lesbian and she/her. description:
Soy ingeniera civil y emprendedora, apasionada por los desafíos que unen personas, ideas y tecnología, y que me eyectan de la zona de confort. Hace poco más de un año inicié mi camino emprendedor, fundando una consultora BIM para acercar el valor de la tecnología a la industria de la construcción. Ese recorrido me impulsó a ampliar mi formación hacia un enfoque más integral, incluyendo mi actual preparación como coach ontológico profesional. Lo que más disfruto es crear vínculos auténticos, en cualquier ámbito. Me fascinan los idiomas: hablo inglés e italiano, y un poco de alemán, estudiarlos me es altamente estimulante. Soy buzo deportivo, una experiencia que me enseñó autocuidado, trabajo en equipo y calma, porque a 30 metros de profundidad, subir no es opción. Soy ingeniera civil y emprendedora, apasionada por los desafíos que unen personas, ideas y tecnología, y que me eyectan de la zona de confort.

title: "Building through connection" | María de los Ángeles Sager | TEDxBarrioSanNicolasSalon

From politician to painter, Leah Johnson shows how quitting isn’t failure but a creative act of courage and transformation. Leah Johnson is a former elected official turned artist, author, and transformational guide who helps people reconnect with creativity and reclaim their joy. After 25 years in politics—including national campaigns and a city council seat—she burned out under the weight of perfectionism and pressure. Success on the outside felt hollow within.

Her healing began not with policy, but with paintbrushes. Through spiritual and creative inquiry, Leah shed the roles she was told to play and found her vibrant,
title: The Courage to Quit: Small Releases, Big Healing | Leah Johnson | TEDxManitou Springs Salon

What happens when the identity you’ve built your entire life no longer fits? In this TEDx talk, Kendra Brim shares her journey of losing 120 pounds, transitioning from a Division I basketball player to life beyond the court, and building a business rooted in purpose and authenticity.

Through her story, she explores the emotional weight we carry, expectations, achievements, and the pressure to perform, and how stepping out of bounds can actually lead to freedom, growth, and a redefined version of success.

This talk is for anyone navigating transition, questioning their identity, or seeking the courage to embrace the next version of themselves. Kendra Brim is a speaker,
title: Redefining success beyond the court | Kendra Brim, MBA | TEDxBuffalo

description:
In this compelling TEDxAlBateen talk, H.E. Dr. Mohamed Al Kuwaiti, Head of Cybersecurity for the UAE Government, shares a powerful message about trust, awareness, and resilience in our increasingly digital world.

Through real-life stories — including that of a friend who lost everything to a cyberattack — Dr. Al Kuwaiti illustrates how the ripple effects of digital threats reach beyond technology, impacting families, businesses, and even nations. He reveals how the UAE is tackling over 250,000 cyberattacks daily, building not just technical defenses but a culture of vigilance, collaboration, and human-centered protection.

Blending global insight with Emirati values, Dr. Al Kuwaiti urges us to treat cybersecurity not as a technical issue, but as a shared responsibility — a new form of peacekeeping that protects lives, livelihoods, and trust itself.

Key ideas:

- Cybersecurity as a human right, not a privilege
- The rise of cybercrime, cyberterrorism, and cyberwarfare
- Building digi
title: Peace of Mind Is a Basic Human Right, Not a Privilege! | H.E. Dr. Mohammed Al Kuwaiti | TEDxAlBateen
